## 1. File Integrity Monitoring (FIM)

### What It Means

File Integrity Monitoring watches files and directories for changes. It can detect file creation, modification, deletion, unauthorized changes, and unexpected tampering.

### Why It Matters for GRC

FIM supports change monitoring, system integrity, audit controls, and evidence that important files are actively monitored.

### Framework Mapping

| Framework | How FIM Helps |
|---|---|
| SOC 2 | Supports change monitoring and security monitoring |
| HIPAA | Supports integrity and audit controls |
| ISO 27001 | Supports change control and monitoring |
| NIST | Supports system integrity monitoring |
| GDPR | Helps protect systems processing personal data |
| HITRUST-style readiness | Supports integrity monitoring |

### Configuration File (macOS Agent)

```bash
sudo nano /Library/Ossec/etc/ossec.conf
```

### FIM Configuration Block

```xml
<syscheck>
  <disabled>no</disabled>
  <frequency>86400</frequency>
  <scan_on_start>yes</scan_on_start>
  <directories realtime="yes" check_all="yes" report_changes="yes">/Users/lafleur/wazuh-fim-lab</directories>
</syscheck>
```

**What each line means:**

| Setting | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `<disabled>no</disabled>` | FIM is enabled |
| `<frequency>86400</frequency>` | Scheduled scans run every 24 hours (86,400 seconds) |
| `<scan_on_start>yes</scan_on_start>` | Runs a scan whenever the agent starts |
| `realtime="yes"` | Watches for changes as they happen |
| `check_all="yes"` | Checks all file integrity attributes |
| `report_changes="yes"` | Reports content changes for supported text files |

### Commands Used

```bash
mkdir -p ~/wazuh-fim-lab
```
Creates the folder that Wazuh will monitor.

```bash
echo "This is my first Wazuh FIM test file" > ~/wazuh-fim-lab/test-file.txt
```
Creates a test file inside the monitored folder.

```bash
ls -la ~/wazuh-fim-lab
```
Lists all files in the folder, including hidden ones, with detailed info.

```bash
whoami
```
Shows the current macOS username, needed to build the full monitored path.

```bash
sudo /Library/Ossec/bin/wazuh-control restart
```
Restarts the Wazuh Agent so the new configuration takes effect.

```bash
sudo /Library/Ossec/bin/wazuh-control status
```
Checks whether the Wazuh Agent is running.

```bash
echo "New sensitive document" > ~/wazuh-fim-lab/sensitive-note.txt
```
Creates a file to trigger a file creation alert.

```bash
echo "Unauthorized change test" >> ~/wazuh-fim-lab/sensitive-note.txt
```
Appends text to trigger a file modification alert.

```bash
rm ~/wazuh-fim-lab/sensitive-note.txt
```
Deletes the file to trigger a file deletion alert.

### GRC Evidence Statement

Wazuh File Integrity Monitoring was configured to monitor a test directory on the macOS endpoint. Wazuh generated alerts when files were created, modified, and deleted. This evidence supports change monitoring, integrity monitoring, and audit readiness.

