## 3. Security Configuration Assessment (SCA)

### What It Means

SCA checks whether systems follow secure configuration expectations, comparing settings against predefined baselines (mostly CIS benchmarks) and recommending remediation.

### Framework Mapping

| Framework | How SCA Helps |
|---|---|
| SOC 2 | Supports secure operations |
| HIPAA | Supports technical safeguards |
| ISO 27001 | Supports secure configuration |
| NIST | Supports configuration management |
| GDPR | Supports security by design |
| HITRUST-style readiness | Supports configuration review |

### macOS Agent SCA Configuration

```bash
sudo nano /Library/Ossec/etc/ossec.conf
```

```xml
<sca>
  <enabled>yes</enabled>
  <scan_on_start>yes</scan_on_start>
  <interval>12h</interval>
  <skip_nfs>yes</skip_nfs>
</sca>
```

| Setting | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `<enabled>yes</enabled>` | Enables SCA |
| `<scan_on_start>yes</scan_on_start>` | Runs SCA when the agent starts |
| `<interval>12h</interval>` | Runs the scan every 12 hours |
| `<skip_nfs>yes</skip_nfs>` | Skips network file systems |

### SCA Policy Location on macOS

```bash
