## 8. Rule Tuning and False Positive Handling

### Important Concept

Do not blindly disable security rules. False positives should be investigated, documented, approved for tuning, scoped narrowly, and reviewed again later.

### Where Local Rules Live (Manager)

```bash
sudo nano /var/ossec/etc/rules/local_rules.xml
```

`local_rules.xml` is for custom rules only — built-in Wazuh rules (like rule 510) live elsewhere, so it's normal not to find them there.

### Example Local Rule Template

```xml
<group name="local,rootcheck,">
  <rule id="100510" level="0">
    <if_sid>510</if_sid>
    <match>Port '55555'(tcp) hidden</match>
    <description>Known lab false positive for hidden TCP port 55555 on macOS endpoint.</description>
  </rule>
</group>
```

### After Editing local_rules.xml

```bash
sudo systemctl restart wazuh-manager
```
Applies the rule change.

```bash
sudo systemctl status wazuh-manager
```
Confirms the manager restarted successfully.

### GRC Explanation for Rule Tuning

Rule tuning is a risk decision. If a detection is noisy but not harmful, analysts may tune it — but this must always be documented, since suppressing alerts reduces visibility.

